<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-PracticalTip">Practical Tip</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Few nodes, many loops? =E2=86=92 Nodal.</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Few loops, many nodes? =E2=86=92 Mesh.</strong></p></li>
</ul>
<p>Both methods are systematic ways to turn a schematic into a set of simul=
taneous linear equations you can solve by hand or using software.</p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"5">
<li>
<p>Circuit theorems: Thevenin=E2=80=99s, Norton=E2=80=99s and superposition=
 theorems, maximum power transfer and reciprocity theorem</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a <strong>concise, practical guide</strong> to the most i=
mportant <strong>circuit theorems</strong> you listed=E2=80=94each with def=
inition, steps, and a quick example idea.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Thevenin=E2=80=99sTheorem">=
1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Thevenin=E2=80=99s Theorem</h2>
<p><strong>Idea:</strong> Any linear two-terminal network of sources and re=
sistors can be replaced by an <strong>equivalent voltage source (Vth)</stro=
ng> in series with an <strong>equivalent resistance (Rth)</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Steps</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Find Vth</strong>: Open-circuit the load terminals and calculate=
 the voltage across them.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Find Rth</strong>: Deactivate all independent sources</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Voltage source =E2=86=92 short circuit</p></li>
<li>
<p>Current source =E2=86=92 open circuit<br>
Then find the resistance seen at the load terminals.</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p>Replace the whole network with <strong>Vth in series with Rth</strong> a=
nd reattach the load.</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Use:</strong> Simplifies complex networks when you vary the load=
 resistor.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Norton=E2=80=99sTheorem">2=
=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Norton=E2=80=99s Theorem</h2>
<p><strong>Dual of Thevenin:</strong> Any linear two-terminal network can b=
e replaced by a <strong>current source (In)</strong> in parallel with a <st=
rong>resistance (Rn)</strong>.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>In</strong> =3D short-circuit current through the output termina=
ls.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Rn</strong> =3D same as Rth (because it=E2=80=99s the same netwo=
rk).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Conversion:</p>
<p>Vth=3DIn=C3=97RnV_{th} =3D I_n \times R_{n}</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3SuperpositionTheorem">3=EF=
=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Superposition Theorem</h2>
<p><strong>Idea:</strong> In a linear circuit with <strong>multiple indepen=
dent sources</strong>, the response (voltage or current) is the <strong>alg=
ebraic sum</strong> of the responses caused by each source acting <strong>a=
lone</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Steps</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Consider <strong>one source at a time</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Deactivate others:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Voltage source =E2=86=92 short circuit</p></li>
<li>
<p>Current source =E2=86=92 open circuit</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p>Calculate the contribution from that source.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Add all individual contributions.</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Tip:</strong> Only works for <strong>linear</strong> elements (r=
esistors, capacitors, inductors in linear region).</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3MaximumPowerTransferTheorem=
">4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Maximum Power Transfer Theorem</h2>
<p><strong>Statement:</strong> A load receives <strong>maximum power</stron=
g> from a linear source when</p>
<p>RL=3DRthR_L =3D R_{th}</p>
<p>(where RthR_{th} is the Thevenin resistance as seen from the load).</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Maximum power</strong>:</p>
<p>Pmax=3DVth24RthP_{max} =3D \frac{V_{th}^2}{4 R_{th}}</p></li>
<li>
<p>Useful for <strong>communication circuits</strong> and <strong>impedance=
 matching</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3ReciprocityTheorem">5=EF=B8=
=8F=E2=83=A3 Reciprocity Theorem</h2>
<p><strong>Statement:</strong> In a linear, bilateral network (no dependent=
 sources), the current at a point B due to a voltage applied at point A is =
<strong>the same</strong> as the current at A if the same voltage is applie=
d at B.</p>
<p>IA=E2=86=92B=E2=88=A3VA=3DIB=E2=86=92A=E2=88=A3VBI_{A\to B} \big|_{V_A} =
=3D I_{B\to A} \big|_{V_B}</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Mainly used in network verification and antenna/coupling analysis.</p></=
li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-QuickExampleIdeas">Quick Example Ideas</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Thevenin/Norton</strong>: Replace a complicated resistor network=
 feeding a single load resistor=E2=80=94calculate easy load current.</p></l=
i>
<li>
<p><strong>Superposition</strong>: Circuit with 10 V source and 5 A current=
 source together=E2=80=94find branch currents by activating each separately=
.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Maximum Power Transfer</strong>: Audio amplifier output matched =
to speaker impedance.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Reciprocity</strong>: Two-port network=E2=80=94swap source and m=
easurement points and observe same current.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>These theorems are standard tools in circuit analysis and design: they s=
implify networks, help with impedance matching, and verify linear system be=
havior.</p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"6">
<li>
<p>Capacitors and inductors: inductors and capacitors, their characteristic=
s, series-parallel combination of inductors and capacitors; RLC Transients<=
/p></li>
</ol>
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a <strong>complete, exam-ready overview</strong> of <stro=
ng>capacitors, inductors, their combinations, and RLC transients</strong>:<=
/p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Capacitors">1=EF=B8=8F=E2=
=83=A3 Capacitors</h2>
<h3 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-Characteristics">Characteristics</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Stores energy in an electric field</strong></p>
<p>i(t)=3DCdv(t)dti(t) =3D C \frac{d v(t)}{dt}</p></li>
<li>
<p>Voltage cannot change <strong>instantaneously</strong> (because that wou=
ld require infinite current).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Energy stored:</p>
<p>W=3D12CV2W =3D \tfrac{1}{2} C V^2</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Inductors">2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=
=A3 Inductors</h2>
<h3 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-Characteristics.1">Characteristics</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Stores energy in a magnetic field</strong></p>
<p>v(t)=3DLdi(t)dtv(t) =3D L \frac{d i(t)}{dt}</p></li>
<li>
<p>Current cannot change <strong>instantaneously</strong> (would need infin=
ite voltage).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Energy stored:</p>
<p>W=3D12LI2W =3D \tfrac{1}{2} L I^2</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Series&amp;ParallelCombinat=
ions">3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Series &amp; Parallel Combinations</h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"d9=
1b98b9-875e-4833-959f-40c826b52eab" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Element</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Series</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
