<p><em>Opposite patterns:</em></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Capacitors add like resistors <strong>in parallel</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Inductors add like resistors <strong>in series</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3RLCTransients(StepResponse)=
">4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 RLC Transients (Step Response)</h2>
<p>When a switch changes position, voltages and currents <strong>transition=
</strong> over time.<br>
Two common circuits:</p>
<h3 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-a)RCCircuit(firstorder)">a) <strong>RC Circuit=
 (first order)</strong></h3>
<p>Charging a capacitor through R from a DC source VsV_s:</p>
<p>vC(t)=3DVs(1=E2=88=92e=E2=88=92t/RC)v_C(t) =3D V_s \left(1 - e^{-t/RC}\r=
ight)</p>
<p>Discharge:</p>
<p>vC(t)=3DV0e=E2=88=92t/RCv_C(t) =3D V_0 e^{-t/RC}</p>
<p>Time constant =CF=84=3DRC\tau =3D R C.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-b)RLCircuit(firstorder)">b) <strong>RL Circuit=
 (first order)</strong></h3>
<p>Current rise with source VsV_s:</p>
<p>iL(t)=3DVsR(1=E2=88=92e=E2=88=92tR/L)i_L(t) =3D \frac{V_s}{R}\left(1 - e=
^{-tR/L}\right)</p>
<p>Decay:</p>
<p>iL(t)=3DI0e=E2=88=92tR/Li_L(t) =3D I_0 e^{-tR/L}</p>
<p>Time constant =CF=84=3DLR\tau =3D \frac{L}{R}.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-c)RLCCircuit(secondorder)">c) <strong>RLC Circ=
uit (second order)</strong></h3>
<p>Series R=E2=80=93L=E2=80=93C with step input:</p>
<p>d2idt2+RLdidt+1LCi=3DVsL=CE=B4(t)\frac{d^2 i}{dt^2} + \frac{R}{L}\frac{d=
i}{dt} + \frac{1}{LC} i =3D \frac{V_s}{L}\delta(t)</p>
<p>Define:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Natural frequency: =CF=890=3D1LC\omega_0 =3D \frac{1}{\sqrt{LC}}</p></li=
>
<li>
<p>Damping factor: =CE=B1=3DR2L\alpha =3D \frac{R}{2L}</p></li>
</ul>
<p>Cases:</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"eb=
361a84-cf61-4bb4-8e97-b44869aa7a86" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Condition</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Response</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Underdamped</strong> (=CE=B1&lt;=CF=890\alpha &lt; \omega_0)</p>=
</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Oscillatory decay: i(t)=3De=E2=88=92=CE=B1t(Acos=E2=81=A1=CF=89dt+Bsin=
=E2=81=A1=CF=89dt)i(t) =3D e^{-\alpha t}\left(A\cos \omega_d t + B\sin \ome=
ga_d t\right), =CF=89d=3D=CF=8902=E2=88=92=CE=B12\omega_d =3D \sqrt{\omega_=
0^2 - \alpha^2}</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Critically damped</strong> (=CE=B1=3D=CF=890\alpha =3D \omega_0)=
</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Fastest non-oscillatory return to steady state.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Overdamped</strong> (=CE=B1&gt;=CF=890\alpha &gt; \omega_0)</p><=
/td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Two real exponential decays, no oscillation.</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-KeyTakeaways">Key Takeaways</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Capacitor voltage</strong> and <strong>inductor current</strong>=
 are continuous across a switching instant.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Combine C and L just like resistors but with <em>opposite</em> series/pa=
rallel rules.</p></li>
<li>
<p>RLC transients depend on <strong>damping</strong> and can oscillate if u=
nderdamped.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>This foundation lets you tackle charging/discharging problems, filter de=
sign, and AC resonance analysis with confidence.</p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"7">
<li>
<p>Series and parallel AC circuits</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a <strong>clear, exam-friendly guide</strong> to <strong>=
series and parallel AC circuits</strong>=E2=80=94how to analyze them and wh=
at to watch for.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3BasicsofACQuantities">1=EF=
=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Basics of AC Quantities</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Voltage/Current</strong> are sinusoidal:</p>
<p>v(t)=3DVmsin=E2=81=A1(=CF=89t+=CE=B8v),i(t)=3DImsin=E2=81=A1(=CF=89t+=CE=
=B8i)v(t) =3D V_\mathrm{m}\sin(\omega t + \theta_v),\qquad i(t) =3D I_\math=
rm{m}\sin(\omega t + \theta_i)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Use <strong>RMS values</strong> and <strong>phasors</strong> (complex nu=
mbers) for steady-state analysis.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Impedance ZZ</strong> (generalized resistance):</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Resistor: ZR=3DRZ_R =3D R (angle 0=C2=B0)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Inductor: ZL=3Dj=CF=89LZ_L =3D j\omega L (angle +90=C2=B0)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Capacitor: ZC=3D1j=CF=89CZ_C =3D \dfrac{1}{j\omega C} (angle =E2=80=9390=
=C2=B0)</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p>Current=E2=80=93voltage relationship:</p>
<p>I=E2=80=BE=3DV=E2=80=BEZ=E2=80=BE\underline{I} =3D \frac{\underline{V}}{=
\underline{Z}}</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3SeriesACCircuits">2=EF=B8=
=8F=E2=83=A3 Series AC Circuits</h2>
<p>All elements share <strong>same current</strong>, voltages add <strong>p=
hasorially</strong>.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Total impedance</strong></p>
<p>Zeq=3DR+j(=CF=89L=E2=88=921=CF=89C)Z_\text{eq} =3D R + j(\omega L - \tfr=
ac{1}{\omega C})</p>
<p>(for an RLC series circuit)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Magnitude:</p>
<p>=E2=88=A3Z=E2=88=A3=3DR2+(=CF=89L=E2=88=921=CF=89C)2|Z| =3D \sqrt{R^2 + =
\bigl(\omega L - \tfrac{1}{\omega C}\bigr)^2}</p></li>
<li>
<p>Phase angle (between voltage and current):</p>
<p>=CF=95=3Dtan=E2=81=A1=E2=88=921=E2=80=89=E2=81=A3(=CF=89L=E2=88=921=CF=
=89CR)\phi =3D \tan^{-1}\!\left(\frac{\omega L - \frac{1}{\omega C}}{R}\rig=
ht)</p>
<p><em>Positive</em> =E2=87=92 circuit is <strong>inductive</strong> (curre=
nt lags).<br><em>Negative</em> =E2=87=92 <strong>capacitive</strong> (curre=
nt leads).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Resonance (series)</strong> when =CF=89L=3D1/=CF=89C\omega L =3D=
 1/\omega C =E2=86=92 purely resistive, current maximum.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3ParallelACCircuits">3=EF=B8=
=8F=E2=83=A3 Parallel AC Circuits</h2>
<p>All elements share <strong>same voltage</strong>, currents add <strong>p=
hasorially</strong>.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Easier to work with <strong>admittance Y=3D1/ZY =3D 1/Z</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Resistor: YR=3D1/RY_R =3D 1/R</p></li>
<li>
<p>Inductor: YL=3D1/(j=CF=89L)=3D=E2=88=92j/(=CF=89L)Y_L =3D 1/(j\omega L) =
=3D -j/( \omega L)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Capacitor: YC=3Dj=CF=89CY_C =3D j\omega C</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Total admittance</strong></p>
<p>Yeq=3DYR+YL+YCY_\text{eq} =3D Y_R + Y_L + Y_C</p>
<p>and</p>
<p>Zeq=3D1YeqZ_\text{eq} =3D \frac{1}{Y_\text{eq}}</p></li>
<li>
<p>Phase angle is determined by the net susceptance (imaginary part of Y).<=
/p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Parallel resonance (anti-resonance)</strong> occurs when total i=
maginary part of Y =3D 0 =E2=86=92 current minimum.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3PowerinACCircuits">4=EF=B8=
=8F=E2=83=A3 Power in AC Circuits</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Real power</strong> P=3DVrmsIrmscos=E2=81=A1=CF=95P =3D V_\text{=
rms} I_\text{rms} \cos \phi (watts)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Reactive power</strong> Q=3DVrmsIrmssin=E2=81=A1=CF=95Q =3D V_\t=
ext{rms} I_\text{rms} \sin \phi (VAR)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Apparent power</strong> S=3DVrmsIrmsS =3D V_\text{rms} I_\text{r=
ms} (VA)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Power factor</strong> =3D cos=E2=81=A1=CF=95\cos \phi (leading i=
f capacitive, lagging if inductive).</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3QuickExample">5=EF=B8=8F=E2=
=83=A3 Quick Example</h2>
<p><strong>Series RLC:</strong><br>
R =3D 20 =CE=A9, L =3D 0.1 H, C =3D 100 =C2=B5F, f =3D 50 Hz.<br>
=CF=89=3D2=CF=8050=3D314&nbsp;rad/s\omega =3D 2\pi 50 =3D 314\ \text{rad/s}=
.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>XL=3D=CF=89L=3D31.4&nbsp;=CE=A9X_L =3D \omega L =3D 31.4\ =CE=A9</p></li=
>
<li>
<p>XC=3D1/(=CF=89C)=3D31.8&nbsp;=CE=A9X_C =3D 1/(\omega C) =3D 31.8\ =CE=A9=
</p></li>
<li>
<p>Net reactance =E2=89=88 =E2=80=930.4 =CE=A9 (slightly capacitive)</p></l=
i>
<li>
<p>Z=E2=89=88202+0.42=E2=89=8820.0&nbsp;=CE=A9Z =E2=89=88 \sqrt{20^2 + 0.4^=
2} =E2=89=88 20.0\ =CE=A9<br>
Nearly at resonance.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-KeyTakeaways.1">Key Takeaways</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Series AC</strong>: Same current, add impedances directly.</p></=
li>
<li>
<p><strong>Parallel AC</strong>: Same voltage, add <strong>admittances</str=
ong> (or reciprocals of impedances).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Use phasor diagrams to visualize phase relationships.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Resonance can dramatically change current or voltage depending on config=
uration.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>These tools let you analyze any R, L, C network under sinusoidal steady-=
state conditions.</p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"8">
<li>
<p>impedance and phasor diagram, series and parallel networks, voltage divi=
der rule, admittance and susceptance</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a <strong>complete explanation</strong> of the requested =
AC-circuit concepts, kept clear and practical.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Impedance">1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=
=A3 Impedance</h2>
<p>In AC circuits, <strong>impedance ZZ</strong> is the generalized =E2=80=
=9Cresistance=E2=80=9D to sinusoidal current:</p>
<p>Z=3DR+jX\boxed{Z =3D R + jX}</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>R</strong> =3D resistance (real part, in ohms)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>X</strong> =3D reactance (imaginary part, in ohms)</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Inductive reactance XL=3D+=CF=89LX_L =3D +\omega L</p></li>
<li>
<p>Capacitive reactance XC=3D=E2=88=921=CF=89CX_C =3D -\dfrac{1}{\omega C}<=
/p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p>Magnitude and phase:</p>
<p>=E2=88=A3Z=E2=88=A3=3DR2+X2,=CE=B8Z=3Dtan=E2=81=A1=E2=88=921=E2=80=89=E2=
=81=A3(XR)|Z| =3D \sqrt{R^2 + X^2}, \qquad \theta_Z =3D \tan^{-1}\!\left(\f=
rac{X}{R}\right)</p>
<p>Voltage=E2=80=93current relationship (phasor form):</p>
<p>V=E2=80=BE=3DI=E2=80=BE=E2=80=89Z\underline{V} =3D \underline{I} \, Z</p=
>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3PhasorDiagram">2=EF=B8=8F=
=E2=83=A3 Phasor Diagram</h2>
<p>A <strong>phasor</strong> is a rotating vector representing a sinusoid=
=E2=80=99s magnitude and phase.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Draw current II as reference (0=C2=B0) or voltage depending on preferenc=
e.</p></li>
<li>
<p>For a series <strong>R=E2=80=93L</strong> circuit:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Voltage across R is in phase with I.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Voltage across L leads I by +90=C2=B0.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Total voltage =3D vector sum of the two.</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p>For a series <strong>R=E2=80=93C</strong> circuit:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Capacitor voltage lags I by =E2=80=9390=C2=B0.</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p>This vector addition gives the total phase angle of the circuit.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3SeriesandParallelNetworks">=
3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Series and Parallel Networks</h2>
<h3 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-Series">Series</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Same <strong>current</strong> through all components.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Total impedance:</p>
<p>Zeq=3DZ1+Z2+=E2=80=A6Z_{eq} =3D Z_1 + Z_2 + \dots</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-Parallel">Parallel</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Same <strong>voltage</strong> across each branch.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Total impedance:</p>
<p>1Zeq=3D1Z1+1Z2+=E2=80=A6\frac{1}{Z_{eq}} =3D \frac{1}{Z_1} + \frac{1}{Z_=
2} + \dots</p></li>
<li>
<p>Often easier to work with <strong>admittance</strong> (see below).</p></=
li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3VoltageDividerRule(ACVersio=
n)">4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Voltage Divider Rule (AC Version)</h2>
<p>For two or more impedances in <strong>series</strong>:</p>
<p>Vk=3DVtotal=C3=97ZkZ1+Z2+=E2=80=A6V_k =3D V_{total} \times \frac{Z_k}{Z_=
1 + Z_2 + \dots}</p>
<p>Because impedances are complex, this gives both magnitude and phase of e=
ach branch voltage.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3AdmittanceandSusceptance">5=
=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Admittance and Susceptance</h2>
<p><strong>Admittance YY</strong> is the reciprocal of impedance:</p>
<p>Y=3D1Z=3DG+jB\boxed{Y =3D \frac{1}{Z}} =3D G + jB</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>G</strong> =3D Conductance (real part, in siemens, S)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>B</strong> =3D Susceptance (imaginary part, in siemens, S)</p></=
li>
</ul>
<p>Where</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Inductor susceptance BL=3D=E2=88=921=CF=89LB_L =3D -\dfrac{1}{\omega L}<=
/p></li>
<li>
<p>Capacitor susceptance BC=3D+=CF=89CB_C =3D +\omega C</p></li>
</ul>
<p>Parallel circuits add <strong>admittances directly</strong>:</p>
<p>Yeq=3DY1+Y2+=E2=80=A6Y_{eq} =3D Y_1 + Y_2 + \dots</p>
<p>then Zeq=3D1/YeqZ_{eq} =3D 1 / Y_{eq}.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-QuickExample">Quick Example</h3>
<p>Parallel R=E2=80=93C branch:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>R =3D 100 =CE=A9, C =3D 50 =C2=B5F, f =3D 60 Hz</p></li>
<li>
<p>YR=3D1/100=3D0.01&nbsp;SY_R =3D 1/100 =3D 0.01\ S</p></li>
<li>
<p>BC=3D=CF=89C=3D2=CF=8060=C3=9750=C3=9710=E2=88=926=E2=89=880.0189&nbsp;S=
B_C =3D \omega C =3D 2\pi 60 =C3=97 50=C3=9710^{-6} =E2=89=88 0.0189\ S</p>=
</li>
<li>
<p>Total admittance: Y=3D0.01+j0.0189&nbsp;SY =3D 0.01 + j0.0189\ S</p></li=
>
<li>
<p>Magnitude |Y| =E2=89=88 0.0215 S =E2=86=92 Z_eq =E2=89=88 46.5 =CE=A9 at=
 angle =E2=80=9362=C2=B0.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-KeyTakeaways.2">Key Takeaways</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Impedance (Z)</strong> combines resistance and reactance.</p></l=
i>
<li>
<p><strong>Phasor diagrams</strong> visualize magnitude and phase relations=
hips.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Voltage divider</strong> works with complex impedances for AC.</=
p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Admittance (Y)</strong> is convenient for <strong>parallel</stro=
ng> networks; its imaginary part is <strong>susceptance (B)</strong>.</p></=
li>
</ul>
<p>Mastering these concepts lets you analyze any AC network quickly and acc=
urately.</p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"9">
<li>
<p>mesh and nodal analysis, wye-delta and delta-wye conversions</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a <strong>concise, step-by-step guide</strong> to the top=
ics you asked for:</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Mesh(Loop-Current)Analysis"=
>1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Mesh (Loop-Current) Analysis</h2>
<p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Find unknown <strong>currents</strong> in plan=
ar circuits using <strong>Kirchhoff=E2=80=99s Voltage Law (KVL).</strong></=
p>
<h3 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-Steps.2">Steps</h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Identify meshes</strong> (independent loops with no interior bra=
nches).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Assign a mesh current</strong> I1,I2,=E2=80=A6I_1, I_2, =E2=80=
=A6 (choose clockwise or counter-clockwise).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Write KVL</strong> for each mesh:</p>
<p>=E2=88=91(voltage&nbsp;drops&nbsp;and&nbsp;rises)=3D0\sum (\text{voltage=
 drops and rises}) =3D 0</p></li>
<li>
<p>Shared elements have voltage drop proportional to the <strong>difference=
</strong> of mesh currents.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Solve the simultaneous equations for all IkI_k.</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Tip:</strong> Best when the circuit has <strong>fewer meshes tha=
n nodes</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Nodal(Node-Voltage)Analysis=
">2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Nodal (Node-Voltage) Analysis</h2>
<p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Find unknown <strong>node voltages</strong> us=
ing <strong>Kirchhoff=E2=80=99s Current Law (KCL).</strong></p>
<h3 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-Steps.3">Steps</h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Choose a <strong>reference (ground) node</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Label unknown node voltages V1,V2,=E2=80=A6V_1, V_2, =E2=80=A6.</p></li>
<li>
<p>For each node, write KCL:</p>
<p>=E2=88=91Vnode=E2=88=92VneighborR=3D0\sum \frac{V_\text{node} - V_\text{=
neighbor}}{R} =3D 0</p></li>
<li>
<p>Include current-source contributions as needed.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Solve the simultaneous equations for all VkV_k.</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Tip:</strong> Best when the circuit has <strong>fewer nodes than=
 meshes</strong> or many current sources.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Wye=E2=80=93Delta(Y=E2=80=
=93=CE=94)Conversions">3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Wye=E2=80=93Delta (Y=E2=80=93=CE=
=94) Conversions</h2>
<p>When three resistors (or impedances) form a <strong>three-terminal netwo=
rk</strong>, you can convert between <strong>star (Y or Wye)</strong> and <=
strong>triangle (=CE=94 or Delta)</strong> to simplify series/parallel redu=
ction.</p>
<h3 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-a)Delta=E2=86=92Wye">a) Delta =E2=86=92 Wye</h=
3>
<p>Given =CE=94 resistors Rab,Rbc,RcaR_{ab}, R_{bc}, R_{ca}:</p>
<p>Ra=3DRabRcaRab+Rbc+Rca,Rb=3DRabRbcRab+Rbc+Rca,Rc=3DRbcRcaRab+Rbc+Rca.\be=
gin{aligned} R_a &amp;=3D \frac{R_{ab} R_{ca}}{R_{ab} + R_{bc} + R_{ca}}, \=
\ R_b &amp;=3D \frac{R_{ab} R_{bc}}{R_{ab} + R_{bc} + R_{ca}}, \\ R_c &amp;=
=3D \frac{R_{bc} R_{ca}}{R_{ab} + R_{bc} + R_{ca}}. \end{aligned}</p>
<p>Where RaR_a is the Wye resistor connected to node a, etc.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-b)Wye=E2=86=92Delta">b) Wye =E2=86=92 Delta</h=
3>
<p>Given Y resistors Ra,Rb,RcR_a, R_b, R_c:</p>
<p>Rab=3DRaRb+RbRc+RcRaRc,Rbc=3DRaRb+RbRc+RcRaRa,Rca=3DRaRb+RbRc+RcRaRb.\be=
gin{aligned} R_{ab} &amp;=3D \frac{R_a R_b + R_b R_c + R_c R_a}{R_c}, \\ R_=
{bc} &amp;=3D \frac{R_a R_b + R_b R_c + R_c R_a}{R_a}, \\ R_{ca} &amp;=3D \=
frac{R_a R_b + R_b R_c + R_c R_a}{R_b}. \end{aligned}</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-WhentoUse">When to Use</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A 3-node network that can=E2=80=99t be simplified by basic series/parall=
el rules.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Common in bridge circuits or unbalanced three-phase loads.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"ElectricalCircuits-QuickWorkflowExample">Quick Workflow Example</=
h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Spot</strong> a =CE=94 of three resistors blocking easy simplifi=
cation.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Convert</strong> to Y using the first set of formulas.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Combine</strong> the resulting series/parallel resistors.</p></l=
i>
<li>
<p>Optionally <strong>back-convert</strong> if needed for final values.</p>=
</li>
</ol>
<hr>
